
CS-350 Portfolio Reflection



Project Summary



Throughout this course, I developed several applications for embedded systems using a Raspberry Pi, along with components

such as LEDs, buttons, a 16x2 LCD display, serial communication (UART), a Morse code state machine, and an AHT20
 
temperature and humidity sensor. My final project integrated these hardware components into a single application that
  
displayed environmental data, responded to user input, and demonstrated how software can control physical hardware.
   
The primary goal of this project was to gain experience in designing, implementing, and troubleshooting embedded
    
systems while also understanding how hardware architecture influences software performance.



Portfolio Artifacts



The two artifacts I selected for my portfolio are:







Final Raspberry Pi Embedded System Application



Morse Code State Machine Application



These artifacts best demonstrate my ability to integrate multiple 

hardware components, develop interface software, implement state 

machines, and troubleshoot both hardware and software issues.



What I Did Particularly Well



One of my key strengths throughout this course was troubleshooting. I learned to isolate problems by testing one

component at a time rather than changing multiple variables at once. This method allowed me to identify issues more

efficiently and minimized unnecessary debugging. Additionally, I organized my code into logical sections, using

descriptive variable names and comments, which made it easier to understand and maintain.



Where I Could Improve



If I were to complete the project again, I would dedicate more time to planning before beginning to write code. 

Although I created diagrams and organized the overall design, additional planning could have lessened the amount of 

debugging required during the integration phase. I would also focus on enhancing my documentation throughout the 

development process instead of waiting until the project was finished.



Tools and Resources Added to My Support Network



Throughout this course, I became significantly more proficient in utilizing various resources such as Raspberry Pi 

documentation, Adafruit hardware documentation, and Python libraries. I also became adept at using GitHub for version 

control and leveraging AI tools to clarify concepts and troubleshoot issues. Additionally, I established a more 

systematic approach to debugging by independently verifying hardware, wiring, and software before making assumptions 

about the source of any problems.



Transferable Skills



The skills I developed during this course will transfer directly to 

future embedded systems, software development, and computer engineering 

projects. These include GPIO programming, hardware integration, state 

machine design, serial communication (UART), sensor integration using 

I²C, hardware and software troubleshooting, and designing software that 

interfaces with physical devices. One of the most valuable lessons I 

learned was not to assume every issue was caused by software. During one 

lab, I discovered that a faulty QWIIC cable was responsible for a sensor 

communication problem after methodically eliminating other 

possibilities.



Maintainability, Readability, and Adaptability



I designed my projects to be maintainable by separating functionality 

into logical sections, using descriptive variable names, and adding 

comments throughout the code. Breaking the application into smaller, 

testable components made it easier to debug individual features before 

integrating them into the complete system. This modular design also 

makes the software easier to extend if additional sensors, buttons, or 

hardware components are added in future projects.


